<chapter id=chapter.platformspecific>
<title/Bugs Occuring Only on Particular Platforms/
<p>
<section>
<title/MS Windows/
<p>

<list>
<item>
On some machines graphical applications get stuck immediately after
startup.
<p>
This problem is related to a bad interaction between Tcl/Tk and some
other background programs. We found that we get the problem if one of
the following programs is running (most liely there are more):
<list>
<item> babylon
<item> fortify agent
<item> sendback
</list>

The problem only appears on Windows NT and not on Windows 95. We
tracked it down that it looks to be a bug in NT itself. We don't know
any workaround yet except to kill the other program, sorry. So we
propose the following: try to kill background programs one after the
other before starting Mozart until Mozart works.

<item> Mozart tries to create temporary files directly under
<kbd>C:\</kbd>. This might lead to two different problems: a user
might not have permission to create files under <kbd>C:\</kbd> and
secondly Windows might get stuck if too many temporary files are
created under <kbd>C:\</kbd>.
<p>
Workaround: set the environment variable <kbd>TMPDIR</kbd> to point to
<kbd>C:\TEMP</kbd> before starting up Mozart for example
by adding <p>
<code>
set TMPDIR=C:\TEMP
</code>
<p>
to your <kbd/autoexec.bat/.
</list>

</section>
<section>
<title/Linux/
<p>
<list>
<item> On some early versions of the Linux 2.2 kernel Mozart might
crash with a SEGV. This is related to a bug in Linux implementation of
mmap.
<p>
Workaround: use version 2.0.37 or upgrade to a newer 2.2 kernel.
</list>
</section>
